docs.abstract: The former vice president had a lot to prove. To those who had written him off after the first debate, he had this to say: “malarkey.”
docs.snippet: The former vice president had a lot to prove. To those who had written him off after the first debate, he had this to say: “malarkey.”
docs.lead_paragraph: One month after a wobbly debate performance that reinforced the perceived weaknesses of the ostensible front-runner — Is he too old? Too nostalgically moderate? Too politically brittle to defend himself when challenged? — former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. settled behind his center-stage lectern on Wednesday night and supplied some answers: He is still old. He is still nostalgic. And he is still the front-runner, until someone can prove otherwise.

headline.main: Joe Biden Did Fine, and That Might Have Been Enough
headline.print_headline: Too Moderate? Too Nostalgic? To That, He Says, ‘Malarkey’

docs.abstract: Groups like the Sunrise Movement helped pressure Democratic presidential candidates to support the Green New Deal. They are now deciding how to use their rising influence.
docs.snippet: Groups like the Sunrise Movement helped pressure Democratic presidential candidates to support the Green New Deal. They are now deciding how to use their rising influence.
docs.lead_paragraph: DETROIT — In April, young activists with the Sunrise Movement, a liberal environmental group, held a rally here at Wayne State University to champion radical steps to curb climate change. Their aim: to get Democratic presidential candidates on record supporting the Green New Deal, which ties traditional goals, like reducing greenhouse gas emissions, with social ones, like ending income inequality and providing free health care.

headline.main: Progressive Activists Have Pushed Democrats to the Left on Climate Issues. Now What?
headline.print_headline: Activists Have Pushed Democrats to the Left on Climate Issues. What’s Next?
